One innovative approach could involve developing a hierarchical graph representation where each cell is modeled as a subgraph of atomic visual-textual tokens (e.g., words or symbols), with edges encoding spatial relationships (e.g., horizontal proximity, vertical stacking, subscript/superscript). These subgraphs could then be embedded using a vision-aware GNN or a transformer equipped with relative positional encodings tailored to intra-cell geometry.

We could further enhance this by introducing contrastive pre-training objectives that encourage the model to cluster intra-cell components into meaningful semantic units based on large-scale annotated tables from scientific literature, patents, or financial reports. This would allow downstream tasks like information extraction, table question answering, or cross-modal retrieval to benefit from richer, more structured cell representations.

The impact potential is significant—this capability would advance automated knowledge extraction from complex documents, improve accessibility tools by enabling semantic navigation of tables, and support AI systems in scientific discovery pipelines. Moreover, it bridges a gap between low-level layout analysis and high-level semantic interpretation, an area where current models still struggle despite progress in document AI.

